'''''Microlarinus lypriformis''''' is a [[weevil]] of the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Curculionidae]].<ref name="ITIS standard report - Microlarinus lypriformis  (Wollaston, 1861)">{{cite web|url=https://www.itis.gov/servlet/SingleRpt/SingleRpt?search_topic=TSN&search_value=187918|title=ITIS standard report - Microlarinus lypriformis  (Wollaston, 1861)|publisher=[[Integrated Taxonomic Information System]]|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> It lays eggs in the stems of the puncturevine, ''[[Tribulus terrestris]]'', and the larvae feed on the [[pith]] of the plant. After [[pupation]], the adult emerges through holes bored in plant.<ref name="University of California Statewide Integrated Pest Management Program - Puncturevine (Tribulus terrestris)">{{cite web|url=http://www.ipm.ucdavis.edu/PMG/WEEDS/puncturevine.html|title=Puncturevine  (Tribulus terrestris)|work=University of California Statewide Integrated Pest Management Program|publisher=[[University of California, Davis]]|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref>  Along with the seed-feeding ''[[Microlarinus lareynii]]'' it has been introduced as a [[Biological pest control#Biological control agents|biological control agent]] in the [[United States of America]]<ref name="University of California Statewide Integrated Pest Management Program - Puncturevine (Tribulus terrestris)"/> and [[Canada]]<ref name="Ministry of Forests, Lands and Natural Resource Operations (British Columbia) - Microlarinus lareynii (Jacquelin duVal)">{{cite web|url=http://www.for.gov.bc.ca/hra/plants/biocontrol/detailed_bioagent_pages/Microlarinus_lareynii.htm|title=Microlarinus lareynii (Jacquelin duVal)|work=[[Ministry of Forests, Lands and Natural Resource Operations (British Columbia)]]|publisher=[[Government of British Columbia]]|accessdate=4 May 2014}}</ref> against ''Tribulus terrestris''.

